data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | App crashes at runtime |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** | Cleanup code never runs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Dead code path |
| `volatile bool` for signaling | Works but not cancellation-aware | Can't unblock waiting calls |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;

        // Task.Run uses thread pool — no manual Thread management
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token), token);
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // Exit loop — no ResetAbort equivalent needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cancellation immediately

        // Wait with timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Task didn't finish in time — log it, but you CANNOT force-kill it.
            // This is by design in .NET 8. Structure code so cancellation is always observed.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)); // best-effort in sync dispose
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

**1. `Thread.Abort()` silently compiles but throws at runtime**
```
System.PlatformNotSupportedException: Thread.Abort is not supported
  on this platform.
```
There is **no equivalent force-kill** in .NET 8. You must make all code cooperatively cancellable.

**2. Blocking calls that ignore the token**
If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a non-cancellable resource (e.g., legacy COM call), cancellation will never arrive. Wrap with a timeout:
```csharp
var item = await Task.Run(() => GetNextItem(), token)
    .WaitAsync(token); // .NET 6+ — throws on cancellation
```

**3. `volatile bool` vs `CancellationToken`**
A `volatile bool` can't unblock a `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitHandle.WaitOne`, or `BlockingCollection.Take`. `CancellationToken` integrates with all of these:
```csharp
// Old — not interruptible:
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// New — cancels immediately:
await Task.Delay(5000, token);
```

**4. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` becomes dead code**
It compiles without warnings but never executes. Audit every `catch (ThreadAbortException)` in your codebase — each one is a silent bug.

**5. Fire-and-forget `Task.Run` loses exceptions**
Unlike threads, unobserved task exceptions are swallowed. Always `await` the task or attach a continuation:
```csharp
_workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token), token);
// Must await in StopAsync or observe in Dispose
```

### For Long-Running Hosted Services

If this runs in ASP.NET Core or a hosted app, prefer `BackgroundService`:
```csharp
public class Processor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}
// Register: builder.Services.AddHostedService<Processor>();
```

This gives you automatic lifetime management, graceful shutdown, and DI integration for free.
